Date:     Thu, 9 Feb 1995 08:30:35 -0500    
Reply-To: UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>     
Sender:   UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>     
From:     Michael Boughn <mboughn@EPAS.UTORONTO.CA>     
Subject:  Re: reified names vs. boundless vocabulary        
In-Reply-To:  <9502081831.AA24193@jazz.epas.utoronto.ca> from "James Sherry" at 
      Feb 8, 95 11:11:58 am     
    
> Every "poem" (every "fact" in fact) is imbued with and attached to a  
> theoretical structure which both informs it and from which it does not    
> separate except in the minds of those who would create a transparent  
> simulacrum of reality where the pure is real. 
    
Excuse me if I sound "misguided" (misguided? isn't that something that  
happens to lapsed catholics and neo-post-trots?), but I'm having a      
hard time with this. My (misguided?) understanding of "theories" is     
that people make them up to explain things. Hence the etymologiocal     
derivation from that whole Greek specular trip: to see (what's      
"behind" the veil). Mr. Sherry's formulation seems to imply that people     
write poems based on theories, rather than writing theories based on    
poems. This may be the way "Language poets" do it, but it hardly seems  
a necessary relation. Perhaps there's a confusion here between      
"theory" and "cosmology".       
    
Best,   
Mike    
mboughn@epas.utoronto.ca        
