From:     Alan Golding <ACGOLD01@ULKYVM.LOUISVILLE.EDU>     
Subject:  Re: reified names vs. boundless vocabulary        
In-Reply-To:  note of 02/09/95 09:12    
    
Associate Professor of English, U. of Louisville        
Phone: (502)-852-5918; e-mail: acgold01@ulkyvm.louisville.edu       
    
Spencer's recent postings on the "level" of art reminded me of Oppen's lines    
from "Of Being Numerous":       
    
One must not come to feel that he [sic] has a thousand threads in his hands,    
He must somehow see the one thing; This is the level of art There are other 
levels But there is no other level of art   
    
In a reading late in life (I think NY, 1979, but I'm not positive) he reads 
this last line as "But this is the level of art."       
    
As regards George Bowering's locating of the Pessoa-in-translation line as  
"What's it all about, Alfredo"--so we've traded the Hokey Pokey for "What's It  
All About, Alfie" now?      
    
Alan Golding    
