     BUFFALO (AHP) -- The day _apex of the M_'s headquarters went up    
 in flames, a bystander caught three of the children as they were thrown    
 from an upper-story window.    
     But just who that man was is in dispute, and the Office of     
 Monitored Sophistry doesn't know who should get a commendation for helping 
 save the children.         
     Four men and a woman have stepped forward, claiming to be the one  
 who caught the children Mar. 15 and carried them to safety.  A fourth child,   
 who jumped from the window after throwing the others, was hospitalized.    
     One of the men, Charles Bernstein, a 45-year-old migrant worker,   
 said he even has a blister, a burn mark and a suit that smells like smoke  
 to prove his story.        
     The Sophist's office plans to honor someone, they just don't know  
 who, said Marjorie Perloff, a spokeswoman for the Monitors.  Another   
 spokesman, Tom Mandel, suggested a bakeoff for determining the hero, but   
 this suggestion was rejected out of hand.  
     In any case, the injured child, Pam Rehm, will receive an award    
 when she is released from the hospital, where she is recovering from burns 
 over 40 percent of her body and scorched lungs. The other children     
    
    
